RNA-seq analysis pipeline

Jérémy Le Luyer

11 mai 2015

Pipeline description

  1. Parallelize jobs in Colosse

    • Script generator for parallelized jobs in Colosse

  2. Data trimming

    • Trimming of the RNA-seq reads (Trimmomatic)

  3. Genome mapping (TopHat)

    • Indexing reference genome (Bowtie2)

    • Align reads on reference genome (TopHat)

  4. Genome mapping (STAR)

    • Indexing reference genome (STAR index)

    • Align reads on reference genome (STAR)

  5. Reads count table

    • Create name-sorted .bam file (Samtools)

    • Create reads count file (HTSeq)

  6. Extracting DE genes (DEseq2)

    • Extract DE genes

  7. Extracting DE genes (edgeR)

    • Extract DE genes

  8. Fonctionnal gene annotation

    • Blast DE genes against uniprot

    • Extract Uniprot_ID for Gene Ontology association (GOminer)

Note: Steps 3 & 5 and 6 & 7 present two identical analyses using different software

Note: Source codes of the software used here are available within the Mugqic pipeline implemented in Colosse ‘apps/mugqic_pipeline/1.2’. For more information about the tools available within Mugqic please contact: assistance@genome.ulaval.ca

1. Parallelize jobs for Colosse

Colosse is specifically made for highly parallelized jobs (i.e 1 job /sample). In this example I will use two samples: Sample1 and Sample2. Data from HiSeq2000 for paired-ends reads give 2 files by sample, namely:

sample1_R1.fastq.gz; sample1_R2.fastq.gz

sample2_R1.fastq.gz; sample2_R2.fastq.gz

Note: R1 and R2 represent left and right senses, respectively

First create a file ‘base_liste.txt’ containing the samples base names:

> ls *fastq.gz | sed 's/R[12].fastq.gz//g'|sort -u > base_liste.txt

> cat base_liste.txt

sample1_
sample2_

Then run the script below, changing ‘script_name’ by the specific script you will use:

> cat generate_script.sh

for base in $(cat base_list.txt); do toEval="cat script_name_template.sh | sed 's/__BASE__/$base/g'"; eval $toEval > scripts_name_$base.sh;done

This command will give two .sh files:

> ls script_name*_.sh

script_name_sample1_.sh
script_name_sample2_.sh

Then, simply launch the scripts in Colosse using:

 > for i in $(ls script_name_*_.sh); do msub $i; done

Note: repeat this for each of the scripts below to increase Colosse efficiency

2. Data trimming

Trimming (Trimmomatic)

Here we remove Illumina adapters & vectors contamination using Trimmomatic

In /home/user_name/ in Colosse, first create a file trimmomatic_template.sh, containing:

> cat trimmomatic_template.sh

#!/bin/bash
#PBS -A _user_colosse_ID_
#PBS -N trimmomatic
#PBS -o trimmomatic.out
#PBS -e trimmomatic.err
#PBS -l walltime=01:00:00
#PBS -M _user_mail_adress_
#PBS -m ea 
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=8
#PBS -r n

module load compilers/gcc/4.8
module load apps/mugqic_pipeline/1.2
module load mugqic/java/jdk1.7.0_60
module load mugqic/trimmomatic/0.32

base=__BASE__

java -XX:ParallelGCThreads=1 -Xmx22G -cp $TRIMMOMATIC_JAR org.usadellab.trimmomatic.TrimmomaticPE \
        -phred33 \
        "$base"R1.fastq.gz \
        "$base"R2.fastq.gz \
        "$base"R1.paired.fastq.gz \
        "$base"R1.single.fastq.gz \
        "$base"R2.paired.fastq.gz \
        "$base"R2.single.fastq.gz \
        ILLUMINACLIP:/home/user_name/univec_trimmomatic.fasta:2:20:7 \
        LEADING:20 \
        TRAILING:20 \
        SLIDINGWINDOW:30:30 \
        MINLEN:60

Note: univec_trimmomatic.fasta needs to be downloaded in home/user_name/ before running the script

Note: the parameters are quite stringent and might be modificated please visit: http://www.usadellab.org/cms/uploads/supplementary/Trimmomatic/TrimmomaticManual_V0.30.pdf

Note: we only keep the .paired.fastq.gz files for the next steps

Note: consider add an additional QC check for your trimmed reads using FASTX-toolkit: Please see http://hannonlab.cshl.edu/fastx_toolkit/

3. Genome mapping (Tophat)

Genome indexing (bowtie2)

> cat tophat_index_template.sh

#!/bin/bash
#PBS -A _user_colosse_ID_
#PBS -N tophat.index
#PBS -o tophat.index.out
#PBS -e tophat.index.err
#PBS -l walltime=24:00:00
#PBS -M _user_mail_adress_
#PBS -m ea 
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=8
#PBS -r n

module load compilers/gcc/4.8  apps/mugqic_pipeline/2.1.1
module load mugqic/tophat/2.0.14
module load mugqic/bowtie2/2.2.5
module load mugqic/samtools/1.2

bowtie2-build /home/_user_name_/genome.fa genome_b2.ref

Note: need to have genome.fa in /home/user_name/

Note: ideally use chr.fa + ScaffoldNotPlaced.fa files

Note: sequences for rainbow trout can be find here: http://www.genoscope.cns.fr/trout/data/

Note: allocation time ‘#PBS -l walltime=24:00:00’ should be adapted to the real needs

To download and uncompress for example ‘Oncorhynchus_mykiss_chr.fa.gz’ from the website in Colosse use:

> wget http://www.genoscope.cns.fr/trout/data/Oncorhynchus_mykiss_chr.fa.gz
> gunzip Oncorhynchus_mykiss_chr.fa.gz

Align reads on the reference genome (TopHat)

> cat tophat_align_template.sh

#!/bin/bash
#PBS -A _user_colosse_ID_
#PBS -N tophatAlign__BASE__
#PBS -o tophatAlign__BASE__.out
#PBS -e tophatAlign__BASE__.err
#PBS -l walltime=24:00:00
#PBS -M _user_mail_adress_
#PBS -m ea 
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=8
#PBS -r n

base=__BASE__

module load compilers/gcc/4.8  apps/mugqic_pipeline/2.1.1
module load mugqic/tophat/2.0.14
module load mugqic/bowtie2/2.2.5
module load mugqic/samtools/1.2

tophat -o tophat_out_"$base" -G genome_annot.gff -p 8 genome_b2.ref "$base"R1.paired.fastq.gz "$base"R2.paired.fastq.gz

Note: You need to download the .gff annotation file corresponding to your genome.fa

Note: Consider an additional mapping QC using Samstat: Please see: http://samstat.sourceforge.net/

4. Genome mapping (STAR)

Genome indexing (STAR index)

create STAR_index_template.sh:

> cat STAR_index_template.sh

#!/bin/bash
#PBS -A _user_Colosse_ID_
#PBS -N STAR_index
#PBS -o STAR_index.out
#PBS -e STAR_index.err
#PBS -l walltime=24:00:00
#PBS -M _user_mail_adress_
#PBS -m ea 
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=8
#PBS -r n

module load compilers/gcc/4.8  apps/mugqic_pipeline/2.1.1
module load mugqic/blat/36
module load mugqic/star/2.4.0k

mkdir /path/to/genomeDirChr

STAR --runThreadN 1 \
  --runMode genomeGenerate \
  --genomeDir /path/to/genomeDirChr \
    --genomeFastaFiles /path/to/genome.fa \
    --sjdbOverhang 99 \
    --genomeChrBinNbits 10 \
    --limitGenomeGenerateRAM 20000000000

Note: .gff is not included in the indexing step with STAR

Note: genomeDirChr needs to be empty prior to launch STAR index

Align of reference genome (STAR)

Create STAR_align_template.sh:

> cat STAR_align_template.sh

#!/bin/bash
#PBS -A _user_Colosse_ID_
#PBS -N STAR_align__BASE__
#PBS -o STAR_align__BASE__.out
#PBS -e STAR_align__BASE__.err
#PBS -l walltime=24:00:00
#PBS -M _user_mail_adress_
#PBS -m ea 
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=8
#PBS -r n

module load compilers/gcc/4.8  apps/mugqic_pipeline/2.1.1
module load mugqic/blat/36
module load mugqic/star/2.4.0k

base=__BASE__

STAR --runThreadN 8 \
  --genomeDir genomeDirChr \
    --readFilesIn /path/to/"$base"R1.paired.fastq.gz /path/to/"$base"R2.paired.fastq.gz \
    --readFilesCommand zcat \
    --sjdbGTFfile /path/to/genome_annot.gff \
    --outFileNamePrefix STAR_alignChr_"$base"

Note: .gff is used at this step

5. Reads count tables

Sort .bam file by names

Using sammtools to create names-sorted .bam files to further use in HTSeq.

Create samtoolsSort_names_template.sh:

> cat samtoolsSort_names_template.sh

#!/bin/bash
#PBS -A _user_colosse_ID_
#PBS -N samtoolsSort__BASE__
#PBS -o samtoolsSort__BASE__.out
#PBS -e samtoolsSort__BASE__.err
#PBS -l walltime=06:00:00
#PBS -M _user_mail_adress_
#PBS -m ea 
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=8
#PBS -r n

module load compilers/gcc/4.8  apps/mugqic_pipeline/2.1.1
module load mugqic/tophat/2.0.14
module load mugqic/bowtie2/2.2.5
module load mugqic/samtools/1.2

base=__BASE__

samtools sort -n tophat_out_"$base"/accepted_hits.bam tophat_out_"$base"/tophat_"$base"NamesSorted

Note: Despite HTSeq ‘normally’ using also position-sorted .bam files, bugs still remain and names-sorted are thus prefered

Create reads-count files

Create HTseq-template.sh file:

> cat HTseq_template.sh

#!/bin/bash
#PBS -A _user_colosse_ID_
#PBS -N HTseq-countmRNA__BASE__
#PBS -o HTseq-countmRNA__BASE__.out
#PBS -e HTseq-countmRNA__BASE__.err
#PBS -l walltime=24:00:00
#PBS -M _user_mail_adress_
#PBS -m ea 
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=8
#PBS -r n

module load compilers/gcc/4.8  apps/mugqic_pipeline/2.1.1
module load mugqic/tophat/2.0.14
module load mugqic/bowtie2/2.2.5
module load mugqic/samtools/1.2

base=__BASE__

HTSeq-0.6.1/build/scripts-2.7/htseq-count -f bam -s no -t mRNA -i mRNA tophat_out_"$base"/tophat_"$base"NamesSorted.bam genome_annot.gff >> output_mRNA_tophat_HTseq-count_"$base".txt

Note: -s no for non-stranded; -t (for feature) ideally ‘exon’ but here changed for ‘mRNA’; -i (id_gene) changed for ‘mRNA’

Note: HTSeq not implemented in mugqic pipeline and needs to be installed locally in /home/user_name/. Please see for installation and source code: http://www-huber.embl.de/users/anders/HTSeq/doc/install.html

The output files from HTseq-count should look like:

> head -n 5 output_mRNA_tophat_HTseq-count_sample1.txt

GSONMT00000001001  53
GSONMT00000002001   59
GSONMT00000003001   219
GSONMT00000004001   0
GSONMT00000006001   62

Note: Column$1: Gene_id; column$2: reads count

6. Extract DE genes (Deseq2)

Note that pipeline was not implemented for Colosse (in progress) and need to be launched locally in user* computer*

**To import data from Colosse in user machine (here for example importing ‘output_mRNA_tophat_HTseq-count_sample1.txt’ to ‘/Users/jeremyleluyer/Desktop/essai_HTseq/tophat’)

> rsync -avzP _user_name_@colosse.calculquebec.ca:/home/_user_name/ /Users/jeremyleluyer/Desktop/essai_HTseq/tophat/.

This is a simple pipeline adapted from http://dwheelerau.com/2014/02/17/how-to-use-deseq2-to-analyse-rnaseq-data/

This pipeline serves for comparing DE gene expression from RNA-seq (2 conditions x 3) replicates based on a reads-count matrix from HTseq-count

Note: The file names might have changed

First import the DESeq2 library from Bioconductor

source("http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite("DESeq2")

Load the library

library('DESeq2')

Import the data and create the dataset

directory<-"/Users/jeremyleluyer/Desktop/essai_HTseq/tophat"
sampleFiles <- grep("s27",list.files(directory),value=TRUE)

Then check the sampleFiles and the order of the file is correct

sampleFiles
## [1] "s27def.s27b1n2.txt"    "s27def.s27b1n7.txt"    "s27def.s27b3n6.txt"   
## [4] "s27recov.s27b11n2.txt" "s27recov.s27b7n4.txt"  "s27recov.s27b9n6.txt"

According to my files order I then set my conditions to create the dataset: Here 2 conditions def and norm

sampleCondition<-c("def","def","def","recov","recov","recov")
sampleTable<-data.frame(sampleName=sampleFiles, fileName=sampleFiles, condition=sampleCondition)
ddsHTSeq<-DESeqDataSetFromHTSeqCount(sampleTable=sampleTable, directory=directory, design=~condition)

At this step, you have to set your condition order. Note it is the levels order is VERY important to interpret the Fold Change (FC). Here for example we will compare def vs recov

colData(ddsHTSeq)$condition<-factor(colData(ddsHTSeq)$condition, levels=c("def","recov"))

Time to make the comparison ! Note that alpha indicates the FDR (pAdj value i.e the correction for multiple tests)

dds<-DESeq(ddsHTSeq)
res<-results(dds,alpha = 0.05)
res<-res[order(res$padj),]
summary(res, alpha =0.05)
##

Do the MA ploting (for those who want it !)

Print the .png in a separate file use (optional)

dev.copy(png,"deseq2_MAplot_tophat.png")
dev.off()

Save the table in a .csv file for futher use (Blast)

Transform the data:

rld <- rlogTransformation(dds, blind=TRUE)
vsd <- varianceStabilizingTransformation(dds, blind=TRUE)
par(mai=ifelse(1:4 <= 2, par("mai"), 0))
px     <- counts(dds)[,1] / sizeFactors(dds)[1]
ord    <- order(px)
ord    <- ord[px[ord] < 150]
ord    <- ord[seq(1, length(ord), length=50)]
last   <- ord[length(ord)]
vstcol <- c("blue", "black")
matplot(px[ord], cbind(assay(vsd)[, 1], log2(px))[ord, ], type="l", lty=1, col=vstcol, xlab="n", ylab="f(n)")
legend("bottomright", legend = c(expression("variance stabilizing transformation"), expression(log[2](n/s[1]))), fill=vstcol)

Note: The x axis is the square root of variance over the mean for all samples, so this will naturally included variance due to the treatment. The goal here is to flattern the curve so that there is consistent variance across the read counts, and that is what we got

Load required libraries for ploting

library("vsn")
library("RColorBrewer")

Gene-wise dispersion

cds <- estimateTagwiseDisp( cds , prior.df = 12 ) #The amount of squeezing is governed by the paramter prior.df which by default is 10. The higher prior.df, the closer the estimates will be to the common dispersion. The recommended value is the nearest integer to 50/(#samples − #groups). For this data set that’s 50/(6 − 2) = 12.5, so it is equal to the default.

Testing

de.tgw <- exactTest( cds , dispersion="tagwise" , pair = c( "def" , "recov" ) ) ##single common dispersion across all genes

de.cmn <- exactTest( cds , dispersion="common" , pair = c( "def" , "recov" ) )

de.poi <- exactTest( cds , dispersion = 1e-06 , pair = c( "def" , "recov" ) ) #a poisson model (no dispersion)

Note: first group is the baseline for comparison ex: def vs recov

Note: need to adapt which model fits your data

8. Functionnal DE gene annotation

Preparing and uncompress Uniprot database

Download Uniprot-sprot.fa database

> wget ftp://ftp.uniprot.org/pub/databases/uniprot/current_release/knowledgebase/complete/uniprot_sprot.fasta.gz
> gunzip uniprot_sprot.fasta.gz

Indexing Uniprot database for Blastx

> makeblastdb -in uniprot_sprot.fasta -input_type 'fasta' -dbtype 'prot'

Prepare .fasta file of DE genes

Create a list of DE gene names

> awk -F "," '{print $1}' def_recov_deseq2_tophat.csv > list_def_recov.txt

Download and uncompress mRNA.fa file for rainbow trout

> wget http://www.genoscope.cns.fr/trout/data/Oncorhynchus_mykiss_mRNA.fa.gz
> gunzip Oncorhynchus_mykiss_mRNA.fa.gz

Create .fasta file for DE genes using Python script ‘get_fasta_alignedContig.py’

> cat get_fasta_alignedContig.py

#!/usr/bin/python
# encoding: utf-8

"""
usage:
keep_contig.py list.txt Contigs.fna
"""

class Printer:
  def __init__ (self, contigName):
        self.printing = False
        self.contigList = []
        for id in open(contigName):
            self.contigList.append(id.strip())

    def parseLine(self, line):
        if '>' in line:
            tokens = line.strip().split()
            if tokens[0][1:] in self.contigList:
                self.printing = True
                print line.strip()
            else:
                self.printing = False
        else:
            if self.printing == True:
                print line.strip()

import sys

if __name__ == "__main__":
    if len(sys.argv) != 3:
        print __doc__
        sys.exit(1)

    contigName=sys.argv[1]
    printer = Printer(contigName)
    filename=sys.argv[2]
    for line in open(filename):     
        printer.parseLine(line)

Note: This is a Python script, please make sure indentations are correct

Run get_fasta_alignedContig.py

> ./get_fasta_alignedContig.py list_def_recov.txt Oncorhynchus_mykiss_mRNA.fa > def_recov.fasta

*Note: use chmod +x script.sh before try running the script

Blastx against uniprot

> cat blast_template.sh

#!/bin/bash
#PBS -A _user_colosse_ID_
#PBS -N blastx
#PBS -o blastx.out
#PBS -e blastx.err
#PBS -l walltime=00:40:00
#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=8
#PBS -r n

cat def_recov.fasta | parallel -j 8 -k --block 10k --recstart '>' --pipe blastx -db /home/_user_name_/uniprot_sprot.fasta  -query - -outfmt 6 -max_target_seqs 1 -evalue 1e-6 > blastx_def_norm.txt

Note: the allocation time needs to be adapted to the query size

Prepare Uniprot_id for Gominer

Extract uniq Uniprot_ID for a Gene

> awk '{print $1,$2}' blastx_def_norm.txt|awk '{ if (!($1 in a)) a[$1] = $2; else if (a[$1] < $2) a[$1] = $2 } END { for (key in a) print key, a[key] }'|awk -F "|" '{print $2}' > GO_def_norm.txt

The GO_list file should look like:

> head -n 5 GO_def_norm.txt 

Q6P9J5
Q95KE5
P02457
Q1L8Y6
Q9NVD7

Use GO_list in GOminer interface
